                    <h3>Understanding a design challenge:<br />What problems are we here to solve?</h3>
                    <p>I begin by diving deep into businesses and user goals for the project. I use a quadrant system where where I document:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Pain points - business and user needs that we're addressing. Where does it hurt?</li>
                        <li>Goals and KPIs - key performance indicators - outcomes that we should get if we're successful</li>
                        <li>Quick wins - big picture ideas that spring to mind first - often part of a project brief. Sometimes these inform MVP, but mostly it's a way of documenting our assumptions. I'll look to validate (or invalidate) these ideas in my discovery phase.</li>
                        <li>Opportunities to elevate - places where we can go from just solving a problem to delivering a superior experience. This is where I start thinking about ideal future state - what we'd do if we had infinite time and resources. Keeping an eye to the future means we're always thinking strategically and looking to step up our game.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p>What starts as a page in my sketchbook will later become a living document that I share with teams and stakeholders. It lets me get feedback and keep in alignment with business goals and deliverability while always advocating for better customer experience.</p>
                </div>

            </div>

        </div>
        
    </div>

</section>

